  abstract = {We use the self-consistent harmonic approximation (SSCHA) with machine learning interatomic potentials to calculate the effect of \$\textasciicircum\{18\}\$O substitution on the properties of quantum paraelectric SrTiO\$\_3\$ (STO). We find that calculations including both quantum and anharmonic effects are able to reproduce the experimentally observed isotope effect, in which replacement of \$\textasciicircum\{16\}\$O by \$\textasciicircum\{18\}\$O induces the ferroelectric state, and demonstrate that the ferroelectric phase transition in ST\$\textasciicircum\{18\}\$O can be reproduced in a purely displacive manner. We calculate the ferroelectric soft mode frequency as a function of volume, lattice parameters and temperature for ST\$\textasciicircum\{16\}\$O and ST\$\textasciicircum\{18\}\$O, and find that the phase space in which ST\$\textasciicircum\{16\}\$O shows quantum paraelectric behaviour, while ST\$\textasciicircum\{18\}\$O becomes ferroelectric is narrow. Our study shows that machine learning interatomic potentials enable temperature-dependent simulations that include quantum and anharmonic phonon effects, however quantitative prediction of phase diagrams remains challenging due to a lack of universally accurate electronic structure methods.},
  langid = {english},
