  urldate = {2025-12-10},
  abstract = {An integrated analytical framework is presented for the detailed characterization and identification of diverse non-Gaussian laser beams from complex field data at a single transverse plane. By leveraging both amplitude and phase, this approach overcomes the limitations of traditional multiplane, intensity-only methods. The framework employs two complementary models: a perturbation model to analyze deviations from a known analytical base, and an additive modal decomposition model to represent the beam as a superposition over a basis set. The primary outputs are the underlying modal or aberration coefficients, which provide a rich, physically insightful description that is often more valuable than the M2 factor alone. As a key application, these coefficients enable a numerically stable calculation of the M2 value that bypasses instabilities encountered with standard moment-based methods, particularly for noisy fields. The framework’s outputs, such as reconstruction quality and the modal power spectrum, also serve as vital diagnostics for validating the chosen model and basis. This power is demonstrated with a noisy Gaussian beam, where the coefficient-based M2 remains stable and physically meaningful, in sharp contrast to the unphysically large value from standard methods. This work provides a versatile and noise-tolerant tool for the complete physical characterization of a wide range of laser beam types from single-plane measurements.},
