  urldate = {2026-03-22},
  abstract = {Harnessing nonlinear interactions between phonon modes in condensed matter presents a powerful avenue for tailoring material properties for innovative applications in future information devices. Here we report a study of nonlinear coupling between infrared (IR) active and Raman-active phonon modes in rare-earth orthoferrites                                                   ErFe                                        O                     3                                                     ,                 ~                                    TmFe                                        O                     3                                                                  , and                                                   TbFe                                        O                     3                                                                  . To reveal the nonlinear phonon interactions, we resonantly excite IR-active phonons with an ultrashort midinfrared pulse, with its central wavelength tunable in the 3–18 µm (16.5–100~THz) range, and trace the phonon modes in the time domain after the excitation. We identify two main coupling mechanisms: quadratic linear and trilinear, which stand for a nonlinear coupling of the Raman-active phonon with either one or two distinct IR-active modes, respectively. The origin of driving each Raman-active phonon mode is identified and analyzed with polarization-dependent pump-probe spectroscopy. Our results show a strong dependence of the trilinear coupling mechanism on the crystallographic orientation of the sample, thus revealing that only specific phonon modes can exhibit this coupling.},
